# Phase 2 — Confluence Discovery

## CONTRACT — Phase 2

| Constraint | Detail |
|------------|--------|
| **Inputs required** | `_domain_card.md` (cloudIds + candidate spaces), `_discovery/uc_inventory.json` (object names to grep) |
| **Outputs required** | `_discovery/confluence_index.json` (one row per matching page) + `_discovery/confluence_pages/<cloudId>__<spaceKey>__<pageId>.md` (cached body in markdown) |
| **MUST NOT** | Search public spaces or non-listed cloudIds. Stay inside the cloudIds enumerated in P0. |
| **Failure mode** | **SOFT** — domain may genuinely have no Confluence presence. Record an empty index with `searches_run` so P5 doesn't re-search. |

---

## Why this matters

For acquired-company domains, **Confluence is the most likely Tier-1 source** — the original Spaceship/MoneyFarm documentation usually lives in our internal Confluence as either an onboarding/integration page or a BI/KPI definition page. The DWH framework anchors on SSDT comments instead; we have no SSDT, so Confluence is promoted from "nice context" to "Tier 1 anchor".

## Tools (agent-driven via MCP)

The MCP server `plugin-atlassian-atlassian` exposes the relevant tools:

| MCP tool | Use |
|----------|-----|
| `getAccessibleAtlassianResources` | One-time per session — confirm cloudIds match `_domain_card.md` |
| `searchConfluenceUsingCql` | Run CQL queries against a cloudId; returns page metadata (id, title, space, link) |
| `getConfluencePage` | Fetch a single page with `contentFormat=markdown` so we can persist it locally |
| `getConfluenceSpaces` | Use only if `candidate_spaces` in P0 is unverified |
| `getPagesInConfluenceSpace` | Walk a small space exhaustively (<200 pages) when CQL is too noisy |

The agent runs these MCP calls directly. There is also a small helper `tools/uc_domains/discover_confluence.py` for the **post-processing** half: take a JSON list of pages already discovered via MCP and write the canonical `confluence_index.json` + writes any pages the agent has saved into `_discovery/confluence_pages/`.

## Procedure

### Step 1 — Build a search keyword list

From `_domain_card.md` and `uc_inventory.json` derive search keywords:

1. Domain display name + acquisition company name (e.g. `"Spaceship"`, `"MoneyFarm"`).
2. Product line names from the domain card mental model (e.g. `Voyager`, `Nova`, `Super`).
3. Top 5 view names from `uc_inventory.json` (e.g. `v_spaceship_fees`, `v_spaceship_aum`).
4. Source-system names (`Metabase BigQuery`, `Spaceship analytics dbt`).

Avoid generic words (`fee`, `aum`) — they return thousands of unrelated pages.

### Step 2 — Run CQL searches

Loop the keyword list, for each keyword run two searches:

```text
searchConfluenceUsingCql(cloudId=<...>, cql='text ~ "<keyword>" AND type = page', limit=25)
searchConfluenceUsingCql(cloudId=<...>, cql='title ~ "<keyword>" AND type = page', limit=25)
```

Title-only matches go into a dedicated **`high_confidence`** list because the page is likely about the keyword, not just mentioning it in passing. Body-text matches go into **`broad`** and need agent triage.

### Step 3 — Triage results

For every result, capture:

```jsonc
{
  "cloud_id": "...",
  "page_id": "1234567",
  "title": "Spaceship Voyager Fees — KPI definition",
  "space_key": "BI",
  "space_name": "BI / KPI",
  "url": "https://etoro-jira.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/BI/pages/1234567/...",
  "matched_query": "title ~ \"Spaceship Voyager Fees\"",
  "matched_keyword": "Spaceship Voyager Fees",
  "confidence": "high" | "broad",
  "last_modified": "2024-...",
  "labels": ["bi", "spaceship"]
}
```

The agent decides which broad-match pages to fetch and cache — usually only those whose title clearly matches the domain.

### Step 4 — Cache the page body

For every kept page, fetch and save:

```text
getConfluencePage(cloudId=<...>, pageId=<...>, contentFormat="markdown")
```

Write to:

```
_discovery/confluence_pages/<cloudId>__<spaceKey>__<pageId>.md
```

with a YAML frontmatter recording the metadata above. The frontmatter is what `discover_confluence.py` reads to (re)build the index without re-fetching.

### Step 5 — Write the index

`_discovery/confluence_index.json`:

```jsonc
{
  "domain": "spaceship",
  "generated_at": "...",
  "cloud_ids": ["..."],
  "searches_run": [
    {"cql": "text ~ \"Spaceship\" AND type = page", "results": 18},
    {"cql": "title ~ \"v_spaceship_fees\"", "results": 0},
    ...
  ],
  "pages": [ /* same shape as Step 3 entries, plus a cached_path field */ ]
}
```

The `searches_run` list is critical — it's our audit trail that tells the next agent run "we already searched X and found nothing", so we don't waste tokens re-running fruitless searches.

## Anti-patterns

- ❌ Fetching the body of every CQL hit. CQL on `text ~ "Spaceship"` regularly returns 100+ pages, most about Slack channels or random meeting notes. Use the title/body split as a triage gate.
- ❌ Storing page bodies as raw HTML or ADF. Always use `contentFormat=markdown` so `grep`/Cursor can search them.
- ❌ Promoting a body-text match to Tier-1 without reading it. P5's Tier-1 anchor requires that the page is actually about the object, not just mentioning it once.
- ❌ Searching open Confluence cloudIds outside the ones listed in `_domain_card.md`. Acquired-company spaces sometimes leak into the same Atlassian site under different scopes.
